  "texts": [
    "What might make us think otherwise is our tendency to redescribe means in terms of ends -to describe the movements of the fingers in terms of what they achieve, the laces getting tied.",
    "But, says Davidson, introducing 'ψ' and 'φ' as distinct names for actions doesn't entitle us to introduce distinct actions that an agent does.",
    "Rather, he suggests, it turns out that we identify the same (basic) action under different descriptions, some of which do so via that action's consequences.",
    "So, if we describe certain movements of a mathematician's body as her writing out an equation, what we are doing is identifying what she does (move her hands and fingers in certain ways) as the cause of what happens (the equation's getting written down) and we are representing this causal connection as according her intentions.",
    "But if we have to decide which one event is the action, we should say that it is the one that meets only the narrowest description."
  ],
